tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Here's how to create better CTA's in just 3 steps.

1. Use clear action oriented language as your button labels.

Instead of vague labels such as "Click here", "Get Started", "Learn More", consider stronger and more clear labels such as "Sign up for a 30 day free trial", "Download My Free eBook", "Discover Our Latest Offers".

2. Make CTA's visually stand out

Use colours that contrast against the background and pop out, demanding the user's attention. An accent colour that aligns with your brand is oftentimes perfect for your CTA's.

3. Leverage microcopy below the CTA to further incentivise users to push the button

- Use copy and badges that demonstrate social proof ("rated 4.9 by 200+ people on TrustPilot")
- Use guarantees ("30-day money-back guarantee")
- Use copy that creates urgency ("offer valid only for the next 24 hours")<tweet 0 end>

However, my big assumption is that others would need it too. Over the next 90 days, I’ll find out if that’s true. Under this thread, I’ll share daily updates and actions taken for 90 days.

⏰⏰ For now, when you first register (one click), you’ll immediately receive 30 credits at no cost—no card details required. Link in my bio.

Create your first Parser from the UI and start making API calls in seconds.

If you want to integrate it into your business or workflow, DM me with your use case. I’ll give you 100 more credits + 15 minutes of free consultancy for integration and brainstorming on how you can get the most out of it.

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Silence kills trust.

Early on, I’d go heads-down on client work, thinking they’ll see the results when it’s ready. Why would they care how much progress I have made?

But in their world, no updates meant no progress.

Then I started doing quick check-ins. Even if I had nothing big to share, just a rough draft, a small win, or even a roadblock -- I’d send an update.

Everything changed.

Clients weren’t just waiting; they were involved. The relationship flipped from “service provider” to “trusted partner.”

Turns out, most founders don’t just want the work done, they want to know someone’s in the trenches with them.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Congratulations, Elon Musk and Ashley St. Clair on the birth of your child, and though it's none of my business, I'm a bit confused.

Ashley St. Clair is a proud American of white heritage who's Jewish but follows the Christian faith.

She grew up in a patriotic household that instilled in her values of liberty, freedom, and justice.

Her family, deeply rooted in conservative values, provided a strong foundation for her beliefs. 

As of August 12, 2024, Ashley St. Clair is happily married to Johnny Alexander, a well-known businessman and chiropractor in Warrior, NYC. 

The married couple, who have kept their personal life relatively private, welcomed their first child in November 2021.

Dr. Alexander, a renowned figure in his field, complements St. Clair’s influential presence in the conservative sphere. They frequently share glimpses of their life together, from attending political events to enjoying quiet evenings at home.

The couple’s chemistry is palpable, often seen in their playful banter and supportive gestures. Their relationship dynamics reflect a balance of professional ambitions and personal commitments.

Despite their busy schedules, they prioritize quality time, making their bond stronger. The couple’s ability to navigate the complexities of public life while maintaining a strong, private connection speaks to their dedication and understanding.

According to them, their relationship exudes a blend of mutual respect and shared values.

In November 2023, St. Clair tweeted: "Stopping birth control and Adderall was one of the best things I ever did for my mental health."

Musk replied back: "For Sure." 

On February 14, 2025, Ashley St. Clair posted: "Five months ago, I welcomed a new baby into the world. Elon Musk is the father."

That would mean that in ~September of 2024 Ashley St. Clair gave birth to a child that Elon Musk fathered.

You're on your own regarding any further calculations.

This is Elon Musks 13th child by a 4th mother.

Ashley St. Clair asks that her child's privacy be honored. 

A few influencers who routinely engage in posting about others, and in some cases teasing peoples children, weighed in on the audacity of verbal mud slinging as they comforted Mrs. St. Clair about those slinging mud her way.

While this is all I have to say on the topic, Elon Musks' persistent posts about looming population collapse are now making more sense. 

That being said, I'm merely sharing my research and observations, and I'll wait for the Candace Owens segment on this topic for validation of what I've stated.

God bless Mrs. St. Clairs and Mr. Musk's 5 month old child.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: I’m digging @stalwartlabs mail server - kudos to the team! ❤️ 🙏 

The only thing I found relatively annoying was having to build the server behind an existing haproxy server with the autoban kicking in before configuring the proxy protocol - it forced me to learn the CLI to add the necessary entries manually.

Also, if you have other services like I do running or that need 443/SSL, you need to tweak your haproxy configuration so it proxies only the mail server URLs (for JMAP).

I’ve got email fully functional locally, behind haproxy running in a small docker container.  

I don’t use calendar features a whole lot, so it’s a great compromise.  However, once more email clients support JMAP, I’ve ready to go.  

I’m using Let’s Encrypt with Cloudflare for all our domains for automated SSL management (both mail and haproxy).

I chose @emclient for desktop/mobile as it seems to work best rather than Apple Mail/Outlook (I found these email clients buggy).

No earth shattering solution by any means, but I’m just that much closer to reducing my overall cloud footprint. 

Have a few final tweaks to make to level up overall security, but the defaults were a great start. 

Let me know if you’d like to see any of the configuration or if you have questions with any of the setup behind the scenes.<tweet 0 end>

profile.name: devleader
profile.biography: Nick Cosentino | Simplifying software engineering concepts for you | Principal Software Engineering Manager @Microsoft | Creator of @BrandGhostAI 👻

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: What kinds of problems are high-paid software engineers solving?

This was a question that I came across that I thought was interesting. The framing seemed to be specifically which domains the software engineers were working in or specific types of problems that they needed to be solving to be pulling in high salaries.

Different companies and different demographics are going to vary greatly with respect to compensation. Startups might look different from Big Tech. Even startup to startup could look wildly different if there is capital injection or not. Or being in a particular country vs another even while being in the exact same industry.

The direct connection to compensation feels a little bit weird here, so I wanted to highlight that just because these types of challenges get attention doesn't translate directly into high salary. It's not necessarily a causation type of relationship (and to be honest, I don't think it should be the pure focus... but that's beside the point).

The things I've seen are broken down into these areas:
- Delivering high impact in niche areas with great business value
- Being a "multiplier" with other engineers
- Solid business impact consistently across broad areas

To greatly over simplify it, it's like:
Compensation ∝ Value of Deliverables x Surface Area of Impact

But the "types" of focus areas will vary greatly from business domain to business domain. That's also why I mentioned sometimes it's even just making others around you more productive overall in high impact areas. Ultimately these translate into high-value investments for the business.

I'd also like to mention the extreme hyper focus in niche areas feels like a bit more of a gamble to get a very high salary. I think if you happen to have such a skill in niche areas, that's cool, but creating a strategy around trying to get a high salary for a very niche skill feels a bit risky to me.

While I don't think purely focusing on compensation is ideal (if you don't love what you do, you're probably spending a large part of your life not being as happy as you could be), I think there are several ways that you can drive up your perceived value in your career.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Speak with funded startups on Reddit 

Go to r/ycombinator 

Search ‘new’ or ‘hot’ posts 

Find posts with pains that you can solve

Reply within 0-10 hrs for maximum effect 

Try not to dictate or tell them what to do 

Tell them relevant advice based on your lived experience 

‘This is how I do it…’

‘How I’ve done this before…’

Follow up with dm quickly 

Include intro + 5 practical steps that follow on from your comment in 1st dm 

DM example:

‘Hey - saw your post about (pain). I've (experienced this pain in relevant setting e.g. running my agency) and typically go through 5 steps to (solve pain). May not be totally applicable to you, but sharing in case you find any of it useful…

(insert 5 steps).’

I did this and got my client a lead that may convert in 4 weeks when they get funding 

They asked to connect on LinkedIn 

I sent all details over to my client

They’ll connect and follow up using screenshots of the OG post, my reply, and dm convo 

Best case they become a client 

Worst case they are a new connection and we ask for intros to our ICP<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: The One Habit That Doubled My Productivity ⏳

For years, I worked 12+ hours a day but felt like I achieved nothing.
I kept tweaking my schedule, but nothing worked until I made one small change

I planned my day the night before

Here’s why it worked:
🔥 It removed decision fatigue. I woke up knowing exactly what to work on
🔥 It prioritized impact, not busyness. Instead of a long to-do list, I focused on 3 high-value tasks
🔥 It created accountability. When I wrote it down, I felt committed

Key Takeaways
✅ Productivity isn’t about working longer—it’s about working smarter
✅ A focused 6-hour workday beats a scattered 12-hour one
✅ Plan before you start, not while you're in the middle of work

What’s your biggest productivity hack?

profile.name: Founder Confessions
profile.biography: Good, bad, ugly, and anonymous stories about scaling a business. Share your stories anonymously here. 👇

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: When many first-time founders get started, more often than not, they’re playing business rather than doing business.

They tweak the logo. They brainstorm mission statements. They get lost in strategy sessions and industry jargon. It feels productive—but it’s not the work.

"The Work" is the difference.

You know what "The Work" is. It’s the unsexy, unglamorous grind that separates those who talk from those who execute. It’s the late nights when no one’s watching, the early mornings when motivation is nowhere to be found, and the disciplined consistency when excitement fades.

The work is picking up the phone and selling. It’s talking to customers, hearing what’s broken, and fixing it. It’s shipping the product before you feel ready. It’s putting something real into the world and standing by it.

The Work is what separates you.

Most people don’t fail because they can’t succeed. They fail because they never actually start. They get stuck in the idea phase, waiting for perfect conditions, mistaking preparation for action.

But the real builders? They get moving. They make decisions. They adapt. They don’t just think about the next step—they take it.

No one escapes The Work.

Every successful founder you admire had to do the work. There was no shortcut, no secret hack. There was just relentless execution, day after day, long before anyone cared.

That’s the difference.

So ask yourself: Are you playing business? Or are you doing business?<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: I've been working on a simple vision/dream board component for the productivity dashboard part of my browser extension.

The idea is to help keep your dreams and goals top of mind while working in your browser by constantly making them visible on your browser's new tab page. This will allow you to make better decisions when choosing where to navigate next. ✨

I have the basics in place, but the tricky part is making a nice compact dream board layout that looks beautiful in different sizes.

Today, I tested using a masonry layout, but it feels to me like it does not fill the space in the best way in many cases. It's also optimized to nicely display many pictures, while your vision or dream board will likely consist of ~2-10 images.

Looks like I need to go back to the drawing board and perhaps investigate some existing vision board solutions to borrow the best parts. 😅<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Every day, I wake up to at least 3 new DMs on X. 

Reading them prompts me to think about the proper approach to DMs from a user's perspective.

✅ DM that gets responses:

- "Hi [name], I want to buy... but I have a question..." (Prospects→Yes)
- "Hey [name], I just purchased one of your X, and I'm curious..." (Customer support → Yes)
- "Hey [name], I noticed you commented... I hope this post can be helpful for you to grow on X... " (Giving away free value → Yes)
- "Hi [name], I am [name], and I have been following you for a while... Just want to say thank you for inspiring me to..." (Show appreciation → Yes)
- "Hi [name], my name is [x], I am currently a student from thinking about... I would like to get your perspectives on... versus... Would be lovely if you can give me some suggestions?" (Proper intro + ask questions → Yes)

❌ DMs that won't get responses:

- "Hi" (Chat on the spot → No)
- "Hi, I have a few questions. Your post says... Can you explain to me in detail?" (No intro → No)
- "Hi, I'd like to offer you the opportunity to grow your conversion 10X..." (Promotional → No)
- "Hi, do you want to partner up..." (I don't know you → No)
- "Hi [name], I loved how you shared... (Got a response back)... by the way, if you want to, I can help you increase your traffic 100x..." (Hidden promotional DM → No)

Well, my suggestion is always to engage in comments publicly instead of going straight to DM. People are more likely to respond to an avatar that looks familiar than to one that doesn't.<tweet 0 end>

<tweet 0 start>: After months of market research, one thing became clear - loyalty programs are the perfect entry point for digital reputation. Here's where #UPAS_ is heading, and why the $200B+ loyalty market needs Web3 transformation:

1⃣ Major players like Pollen ($150M), Blackbird ($24M), qiibee ($8M) are rushing to build closed systems. Meanwhile, we're creating something different - an open standard that benefits everyone.

2⃣ Technical foundation getting serious upgrades:
* ICRC-1 powered points that never expire
* Delegated keys for true privacy
* Smart receipt tracking with symmetric encryption
* Tag-based reputation computation
* Dynamic cashback tied to reputation scores

3⃣ Businesses don't care about "decentralization" - they want growth. So we're giving them:
* Flexible reward schemes
* Team management through delegated keys
* Private analytics
* Cross-program engagement
* Real customer insights

4⃣ Users finally get what matters:
* Reputation that travels everywhere
* Stack rewards across platforms
* Own your data monetization
* Earn based on your actual value
* No more locked points

5⃣ Everything stays open source. While others build walled gardens, we're creating public infrastructure for the entire ICP ecosystem.

Really hoping @dfinity continues supporting this vision - we're building what could make ICP the backbone of Web3 loyalty. Current market signals show this could be the breakthrough case for ICP's business adoption. 🥷

#ICP<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: The Equation of Extremes: How Outlier Icons Benefit the Center

Imagine society as a vast mathematical formula where every action and idea contributes to an overall balance. In this grand equation, figures like @elonmusk and Kanye West are the statistical outliers: the extremum points that, at first glance, seem to push our collective data toward the fringes. Yet, their radical statements and performances actually benefit those in the center.

Why do these extreme antics help moderate voices rather than polarize opinions further? The answer lies in our nature as social animals. We inherently crave belonging and are reluctant to stand out too starkly. When someone like Musk or Kanye makes a bold, uncompromising statement, it often repels those who prefer the comfort of subtlety. Their flamboyant behavior forces most of us to retreat toward the center, where social acceptance and balance reside.

In mathematical terms, these outliers act as a corrective force. Just as an extremum in a function temporarily stretches the curve before the system naturally re-centers itself, the shock value of extreme performances pushes people away from the fringes and back toward moderation. Rather than deepening societal divisions, their unpredictable acts highlight the appeal of the center.

This concept - what I might call а "balanced impartiality" - is a sound principle for navigating today’s polarized world. By inadvertently recalibrating the social spectrum, the bold moves of figures like Musk and Kanye remind us that the middle ground is a dynamic nexus where stability thrive.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Holding the sequel to the book that predicted our chaotic present with eerie accuracy — 25 years before it happened 🔥

@HoweGeneration’s The Fourth Turning Is Here isn't just another doom scroll. 

It's a fascinating deep-dive into how history moves in predictable 80-100 year cycles, each ending in a massive crisis that transforms society.

American Revolution → Civil War → Great Depression/WWII → Today

That’s the America-centric version, but his and Strauss’ original thesis goes way back to the English War of the Roses and the template has repeated from there.

The signs he predicted:

- Institutional collapse
- Political tribalism
- Economic instability
- Social upheaval
- Rising public anger
- Loss of faith in experts
- Generational conflict

Sound eerily familiar? 

That's because we're living through what he calls a 'Fourth Turning' — a crucial period where old systems die and new ones are born.

The most fascinating part? This isn't about predicting doom. It’s about understanding how these cycles always end in renewal. But first, we have to navigate the storm.

Currently devouring this book and connecting dots I never saw before. The 2020s will reshape everything, but not in the way most expect.

If you want to understand not just what's happening, but why it's happening (and what comes next) — this is your blueprint.

The future is turbulent, but it's not random. And it’s all happened before.

I’ve always loved demographics stuff, and adding the generational material to it is genius. I read original The Fourth Turning book some years ago and it blew my mind back then.

I’ll be doing a few of these book related posts featuring recent reads (and some older ones too). Let me know if you like this kind book intro content? 📚<tweet 0 end>

profile.name: Mihiro Suzuki
profile.biography: going bananas

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Fridges in asian convenience stores are not actually refrigerators. I always wondered why I could eat “cold” good tasting onigiri in Japan.

Its because the temperature is actually set to 60F, with a one day “fridge” lifespan.

Week 26 of Running Experiments to Test Ideas

This week I dove into restaurant marketing, wholesale foods, and premium products.

Japanese restaurant consulting gig learnings
- Revenue drivers were 2-3 main items on the menu
- Marketing should be simple. Their messaging was confusing. Consumers should associate you for some specific product, and the rest are ancillary 

The problem with onigiri at scale
- Fridge temp. Temps in asia are around 60F while its around 40F in America. Thats why the rice doesn’t get hard in Japan.
- Distribution reliance. Distributors will take 30-40% of your product. This kills profitability. You need some sort of leverage when going into the deal or have super good margins.
- Plastic. Plastic wrappers make things look very nice. But it isn't too good to be using it. But it's a problem to be addressed at scale because its way to expensive in the beginning. 
- Customer volume and personas. You have to make so many and the customers are less understanding of the issues you face.

Sell to a small, high paying demographic -> target larger demographic range at scale
- In the beginning, I won’t have much resources to serve a lot of people. Plus the demographic will be more understanding of pricing, issues, and have a strong network. 
- Ultimately I want to take on wholesale generic food distribution. Generic sandwiches and salads are so gross.

Premium product ideas
- Omakase bento box. Pop up style omakase with bento box to take experience home
- Mochi. Mochi ice cream or just pure mochi.
- Soba/Udon. Handmade Soba and Udon. There isn't a place in Austin that sells that yet and has decent margins/preservability<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: How much do you teach your child about financials?

My older kids are now in 5th grade, so I thought it a good time to introduce them to our stock portfolio. They know where to track it (on my phone, with my supervision, obviously, because these days all apps have one-touch buy! 😱), know what kind of stocks to buy (industry you know, uptrending, uptrending fast vs uptrending slow, what do the indexes show, etc), and are the first to know when I just bought or sold or rebalanced our portfolio.

Anyway, today I was doing just that (rebalancing) and with a slip of a finger (goddamn one-touch-buy apps) I bought more stocks of one kind than I wanted.

So, today I'm going to explain to my kids about covered calls. 🤷‍♀️

In the end, the goal is to get them familiar enough with the terms so that when I'm no longer around, they can manage this or their portfolio more or less knowledgeably. It took me a long while to learn and if I had known about stocks and options as a child it would've been much easier and I would've started investing sooner, which, after all, is what makes the biggest difference. 🥰<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Real estate is SO cyclical

1. Rents are up, new starts increase
2. New supply hits market, rents are down, new starts slow
3. Slowed supply raises rents, new starts increase again

Over and over and over. Add in interest rates and the swings can be even bigger.

Colorado's MF market is following almost exactly. Textbook.

So where are we now? Somewhere between close to the bottom, and the bottom. That's what everyone is trying to figure out. The difference between the two in terms of strategy?

Hyper-Supply: Selective buy and hold - Stay put with buy and hold of properties.
Recession: Invest - Investing in foreclosures, distressed assets and bank-owned homes at great prices.

As more and people determine that we have indeed seen the bottom, the shift form a buy & hold to an investment mindset. We'll know we're fully there when volume picks back up to 2019ish levels.<tweet 0 end>

profile.name: Ciara Wearen
profile.biography:
Mission: empower people to build with AI tools.
Proven results from students worldwide @100schoolHQ
Prompt Driven Developer | Resident AI Builder ⬆️

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: There’s a clear split happening in AI coding tools for how people learn and build. Using a local code editor like Cursor forces you to actually engage with the code, debug and structure your workflow while web based tools like Lovable abstract most of that away.

For me the biggest benefit of using Cursor is the constant back and forth with AI not just getting full solutions handed to me. It also exposes me to complex concepts I wouldn’t have even known to look for.

On the other hand tools like Bolt or v0 focus on ease and speed which is great for prototyping and non-tech users. They’re basically becoming no-code tools. 

Both approaches are valid but they serve totally different audiences. I’m not saying one is better than the other. From my experience they're just different.

The trade off for ease is abstraction and abstraction slows down actual learning. If you’re using Cursor or Windsurf you’re already ahead of the curve.<tweet 0 end>

<tweet 0 start>: Say Goodbye to Endless Influencer Searches!

Today we are thrilled to introduce the newest version of AutoGather — the world’s first AI Agent for marketers who are tired of spending hours digging through social media to find the perfect influencers.

The problem:
Influencer marketing is exploding, but hours of work is spent on manual research—scrolling, filtering, and guessing who aligns with your product or brand. It’s time-consuming, frustrating, and honestly… outdated.

How Autogather works:
Tell our AI exactly what you need in plain English (e.g., “Find TikTok influencers who have talked about AI companions or mental health apps, are suitable for promoting my AI app, with 50k - 5M followers”), and within seconds, get a curated list of influencers with detailed assessments and reasons why they match your criteria.
No more endless keyword searches, filters, sifting through profiles. Just results.

The idea came to us when we built https://t.co/pzObLq3jrj’s first version (an AI agent that autonomously gathers web data into spreadsheets), we noticed a lot of beta users were marketers scrambling to find influencers. And many friends who are SaaS startups founders also have this painpoint. And we think this is exactly the use case what AI Agent should help and fully automate and the results are measurable and verifiable.

Try it here 👉 https://t.co/SEEewVfmok

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: I was going to just post this picture of plant stands I made but it ended up as tips to avoid burnout 👇

I'm heading to Ireland/UK in a few days for my first full day off in months.

I feel like I can keep going but I do notice some signs that have led to burnout before. Silly mistakes, lack of appetite, and increased blood pressure are a few.

It's been a good streak and finding better ways to weave in life and keep up the intensity. Here are some habits that are working well for me and may work for you also:

- Morning workouts while listening to audiobooks 

Start the day with a different perspective while increasing your energy capacity. This is a non-negotiable for me.

- 2 daily walks

After lunch and after dinner to help digestion, get fresh air, relax eyes, move body, and catch up with my wife/talk about nonsense, or the meaning of life.

- Make it easy to eat healthy

Meal prep, snack prep, shopping prep. The difference in energy levels and brain clarity are huge going from junk to healthy foods.

- Enjoy your work

Easier said than done, I know. But if you get excited about your work and do so while talking about it, you can also inspire others and become an energy fountain. 

- Take intentional screen breaks

Rest your eyes and brain in set breaks by holding a plank, stretching your spine by hanging, timed chore challenges, or working on a hobby for a little bit.

One of my hobbies recently has been woodwork as I thought it was fitting as there's a lot of wood in Canada. Oh yeah, here's that picture of some plant stands I made: 

#buildinpublic<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: This is the biggest waste of time ever. 

You can literally get stuck for days if working with a large code base. I've been there, it's not a good place to be.

Here's what i started doing to mitigate that:

1 - Always review the code that AI is modifying. Treat it like a PR review, don't be lazy, if you hire a developer you will review their PRs, you should do the same with AI.

2 - Let AI work on smaller tasks, break one generic prompt into multiple smaller prompts.

3 - Commit your code after every successful change for damage control.

4 - If one model is not working for a specific prompt, try switching to different models even if the other model is usually dumber.

5 - Don't forget that you are a developer, code the critical parts yourself.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Wondering how blind (or visually impaired) people play cricket? Here's a short explanation:

1. Both teams have the same number of players as regular teams (11 on each side).

2. Players are classified into three categories based on their level of visual impairment:
   - B1: Totally blind
   - B2: Partially sighted
   - B3: Partially sighted with better vision than B2(highest level of partial sight allowed).

Team Composition - Teams have 11 players total
->4 players must be B1 (totally blind)
->3 players must be B2 (partially blind)
->4 players must be B3 (partially sighted)

This classification system helps ensure fair competition by grouping players with similar levels of visual impairment

3. When a totally blind player is bowling, they wait for the wicketkeeper (the player standing behind the batsman/striker) to give an audio signal by saying "here-here-here." The blind bowler then throws the ball in the direction of the sound.

4. If a totally blind player (B1) scores 1 run, it is counted as 2 runs.

5. Each team plays for 20 overs. 1 over has 6 throws, so every team get a chance of max 120 strikes. It takes around 90min for one side to complete batting. 

see this attached demo video.  @blind_cricket @VistaCenterNews<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Why trying to sell less might actually sell more: 
 
Have you ever noticed that sometimes the harder you push to sell something, the more your customers pull away? 
 
👉 It's a classic sales paradox: sometimes, selling less really does mean selling more. 
 
People hate being sold to, but they love to buy. 
 
The key lies in creating an environment where buying from you feels like their idea. 
 
It's about drawing them in, not pushing them to make a decision. 
 
This concept isn't new, but it's becoming increasingly relevant in a world where we are bombarded with choices. 
 
They’re looking for trust, for a connection that feels genuine. 
 
👉 As entrepreneurs, it's our job to build that trust, to approach sales as a service we're providing, not just a product we're pushing. 
 
Start by understanding the needs and wants of your customers. 
 
Listen more than you speak. 
 
Show that you care about them, not just about closing a deal. 
 
And when you do offer a solution, make sure it truly aligns with what they're looking for. 
 
When you shift from selling to serving, you create loyal customers who come back for more and bring their friends with them. 
 
It’s a strategy not just for making sales, but for building relationships that sustain your business long term. 
 
So next time you’re planning your sales strategy, ask yourself: 
 
🔹 Am I pushing too hard? 
 
🔹 Could I achieve more by easing back? 
 
Sometimes, less is indeed more when it comes to selling. 
 
Let's rethink how we approach sales, focusing less on quotas and more on quality interactions. After all, isn't that what we're all truly selling? 
 
Image: Studio Petits Pois Carottes<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: How to test your SaaS homepage copy’s clarity

1. Ask five to seven people separately for their first impressions. Keep it simple: “What do you think my product does?” or “Who do you think this is for?”

2. Time their response. If they can articulate your UVP in 10 seconds, your messaging is likely clear.

3. Look for consistency. If most answers are similar, your homepage is doing its job. If responses vary widely, your messaging is vague and needs refining.

Pro tip:

Test with people outside your industry. If a layperson gets it, your target audience definitely will.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: What you work with breaks down

Here's what a fitness trainer who became a world champion bodybuilder at age 51 told about his sore joints, ligament damage and his other injuries.

His idea was simple - what you work, you break.

- Miners have sore lungs and bones
- Truckers have back problems.
- Singers have torn ligaments and broken voices.
- Lawyers often have heart problems and alcohol problems.

The question remains - what breaks down in IT professionals?

What breaks down, of course, is the psyche.

Depression, anxiety, ADHD, stress, burnout - it's all about IT and online jobs.

Every second person has mood problems.

Some are on antidepressants, some drink, and some blow.

Take care of yourself.

Don't take on too much, move more.

If you feel like there's something wrong with your mood, it's not your mood and it's time to see a doctor. ❤️<tweet 0 end>

profile.name: Julia Yu
profile.biography:
🦄 Co-founder at @UnicornsVC
🤝  Help startups (Pre-Seed  →  Seed) & VCs find each other

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Monetization vs. Investments: Can You Raise Serious Investment at the Pre-Revenue Stage Today?

Duolingo operated without monetization for four years. The team focused solely on user retention and relied on investments to sustain itself.

Product Hunt followed a similar path. For the first four years, Ryan Hoover attracted investors and users, and when asked about monetization, he responded with something like:
“We have hypotheses, and we’re working on them.”

After four years, they launched ads. Later, they experimented with SaaS (which didn’t work out), and in the last two years, they experienced significant growth with an ad-based model.

Why Were Duolingo and Product Hunt Able to Do This?

🟢 Duolingo secured funding because:

1️⃣ Luis von Ahn was a successful entrepreneur — his previous project, reCAPTCHA, was acquired by Google. Investors love founders who have built big success stories before.
2️⃣ Innovative business model — venture investors believed Duolingo could generate revenue without forcing users to pay directly.

🟠 Product Hunt attracted investment because:

1️⃣ Ryan Hoover was an active member of the startup community. He had strong connections with well-known entrepreneurs and investors from Y Combinator, AngelList, and other VC networks.
2️⃣ Strong organic growth. Product Hunt quickly gained popularity among founders and investors because it solved a real problem—helping startups find early users and receive feedback.
3️⃣ Network effect. The more startups listed their products, the more investors and users joined the platform, creating a self-sustaining growth loop.

In both cases, investors understood:

If a project is growing fast, it can be monetized later, once it reaches a critical mass of users. Monetization too early could slow down growth.

But Can the Same Strategy Work Today?

During our customer development calls with funds that invest at the pre-seed and seed stages, we ask about their key selection criteria.
Every single one of them says they are not interested in pre-revenue startups. You might get $50K to test marketing—but nothing more.

To secure a substantial investment, you need:
✅ A warm connection with the investor.
✅ An impressive track record with past successful cases.
✅ A strong Founder-Market Fit.

In all other cases: attract users and generate revenue.<tweet 0 end>
